{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Tuning differential evolution hyperparameters\n",
    "\n",
    "Similar to most machine learning models, the hyperparameters that work best for any particular solver will differ based on the problem at hand. This notebook illustrates the effect each hyperparameter of the differential evolution (DE) solver has on the convergence of a search. Much research has been done on tuning these parameters, however there is no agreed upon solution to choosing a value for every problem.\n",
    "\n",
    "For an overview of the main hyperparameters in DE, refer to the [solver user guide](../04_user_guide/03_solver.md).\n",
    "\n",
    "The recommended ranges and some intuition around hyperparameters was borrowed from [this survey](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/220380793) on the DE state of the art."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Setup\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll be solving the [Ackley function](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ackley_function) in five dimensions. This function has its optimum at $\\mathbf{x}^* = [0, 0, 0, 0, 0]$ with $f(\\mathbf{x}^*) = 0$. To save some code, we'll set up a `solve` and `plot` function to visualize our searches over multiple seeds."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "from optimizer.testing.problems import Ackley\n",
    "from optimizer.solvers import DifferentialEvolutionSolver\n",
    "\n",
    "dimension = 5\n",
    "ackley = Ackley()\n",
    "bounds = ackley.bounds(dimension)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def solve(\n",
    "    strategy_=\"best1bin\", \n",
    "    popsize_=75, \n",
    "    mutation_=(0.5, 1.0), \n",
    "    recombination_=0.7, \n",
    "    maxiter=100, \n",
    "    runs=30\n",
    "):\n",
    "    \"\"\" Default arguments here are defaults in `DifferentialEvolutionSolver`. \"\"\"\n",
    "    best_objectives = np.empty((runs, maxiter))\n",
    "    population_variances = np.empty((runs, maxiter))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for i in range(runs):\n",
    "        solver = DifferentialEvolutionSolver(\n",
    "            bounds, \n",
    "            seed=i, \n",
    "            strategy=strategy_, \n",
    "            popsize=popsize_, \n",
    "            mutation=mutation_,\n",
    "            recombination=recombination_,\n",
    "            maxiter=maxiter - 1\n",
    "        )\n",
    "        \n",
    "        bests = []\n",
    "        variances = []\n",
    "        while not solver.stop():\n",
    "            x = solver.ask()\n",
    "            f_x = ackley(x)\n",
    "            solver.tell(x, f_x)\n",
    "            \n",
    "            bests.append(solver.best()[1])\n",
    "            variances.append(np.var(solver.parameters))\n",
    "        \n",
    "        best_objectives[i] = bests\n",
    "        population_variances[i] = variances\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return best_objectives, population_variances"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot(bests_, variances_, labels_):\n",
    "    fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, figsize=(15, 7), sharex=True)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for best_, vars_, label_ in zip(bests_, variances_, labels_):\n",
    "        stdev = np.sqrt(vars_.mean(axis=0))\n",
    "        mean_best = best_.mean(axis=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "        ax[0].plot(mean_best, label=label_)\n",
    "        ax[0].fill_between(np.arange(best_.shape[1]), mean_best - stdev, mean_best + stdev, alpha=0.2)\n",
    "        ax[1].plot(stdev, label=label_)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax[0].set_ylabel(\"Mean Best Objective Value\"), ax[1].set_ylabel(\"Population Standard Deviation\")\n",
    "    ax[0].legend(), ax[1].legend()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return ax"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Effect of `strategy`\n",
    "\n",
    "The `strategy` argument controls the mutation strategy used to generate new solutions. The community characterizes different strategies with a 3-part naming scheme of the form `x/y/z`.\n",
    "- `x`: the base vector being changed.\n",
    "- `y`: the number of difference vectors used to change `x`.\n",
    "- `z`: set to `bin` or `exp` to denote binomial or exponential crossover. Binomial crossover is most common and successful.\n",
    "\n",
    "The default choice for `strategy` in `DifferentialEvolutionSolver` is `best/1/bin` as this has been shown to be effective on a wide variety of problems. In general if you know your problem if unimodal, using a strategy that involves perturbing the current best in the population is a good idea. If the problem is multi-modal a strategy like `rand/1/bin` may be more appropriate to maintain population diversity. Population diversity refers to how different the solutions in the current population are. We can simply measure this with the standard deviation of the population.\n",
    "\n",
    "The choice of strategy is unique to DE and so we simply recommend the user to try `best/1/bin` or `rand/1/bin` on their problem as a good starting point. The formula for these rules are:\n",
    "\n",
    "`rand/1/bin`:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{v}_{i} = \\mathbf{x}_a + F * (\\mathbf{x}_b - \\mathbf{x}_c)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where $\\mathbf{v}_i$ is referred to as a mutant for population index $i$, $a\\neq b \\neq c \\neq i$ are random indices in the population, and $F$ is the mutation factor (referred to as `mutation` in the `DifferentialEvolutionSolver`).\n",
    "\n",
    "`best/1/bin`:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{v}_{i} = \\mathbf{x}_{\\text{best}} + F * (\\mathbf{x}_a - \\mathbf{x}_b)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where all $a \\neq b \\neq i$ as before and $\\mathbf{x}_{\\text{best}}$ is the current best solution vector.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here, we'll observe the effect of the choice on the mean best objective value and standard deviation of the current DE stored parameter matrix (or population)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x504 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "strategies = [\"best1bin\", \"rand1bin\"]\n",
    "bests, variances = list(zip(*[solve(strategy_=s) for s in strategies]))\n",
    "plot(bests, variances, strategies);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Its clear from the plots that the standard deviation of the current population decreases faster for `best/1/bin`. Consider the formula for this update rule. Using $\\mathbf{x}_{\\text{best}}$ in the mutation strategy pulls new solutions toward the best solution along dimensions that make it into child vectors in the crossover step. Because of this, the search converges to an optimum faster. This is a double edged sword: one may obtain a solution faster but there is no guarantee that it will be good. The strategy `rand/1/bin` shows more diversity from the standard deviation plot but converges more slowly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Effect of `popsize`\n",
    "\n",
    "Population size is a more direct control on how diverse any one given DE population will be. In general, it is recommended to increase population size linearly with the dimension of the problem. There are many recommendations on how to do this, by default `DifferentialEvolutionSolver` sets the population size to $n=15d$ for a $d$-dimensional problem. Other recommendations have been made as low as $n=3d$ for this parameter. \n",
    "\n",
    "Practically speaking, population size is usually limited by computation. Any population based algorithm will begin to run slowly due to effort spent creating and evaluating new solutions as population size increases. A good rule of thumb is to pick a population size that balances convergence time and final objective value. Obviously we want the best possible objective, but not at the sacrifice of fast convergence."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x504 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "popsizes = [5, 10] + [i * dimension for i in range(5, 16, 5)]\n",
    "bests, variances = list(zip(*[solve(popsize_=p) for p in popsizes]))\n",
    "plot(bests, variances, [\"$n={}$\".format(p) for p in popsizes]);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can see here that, for the default values of `mutation` and `recombination`, population size stops making a big difference in convergence rate after $n=50$. Therefore, in this case, there's no real reason to use a population size outside the range of $25$ to $50$. The population size $n=5$ (the lowest possible population size for `DifferentialEvolutionSolver`) is clearly too small since the population converges quite slowly to a poor solution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Effect of `mutation`\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider again the `rand/1/bin` strategy for mutation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{v}_{i} = \\mathbf{x}_a + F * (\\mathbf{x}_b - \\mathbf{x}_c)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Here, $F$ is the mutation factor (has many names in literature). This hyperparameter can be thought of as the step size of DE. The original implementation of DE recommends $F$ be in the range $[0.4, 1]$. The implementation in `DifferentialEvolutionSolver` also supports \"dithering\" which refers to choosing $F$ from a uniform distribution each generation. In order to use this feature, simply supply a tuple of the form $(F_{min}, F_{max})$. Dithering has been shown to increase the reliability of DE convergence on some problems."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x504 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mutations = [(0.5, 1.0), 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1]\n",
    "bests, variances = list(zip(*[solve(mutation_=m) for m in mutations]))\n",
    "plot(bests, variances, [\"$F={}$\".format(m) for m in mutations]);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For the smaller values of $F=0.1,0.25$ convergence happens quite quickly to a non-optimal. From this we can infer that the algorithm is taking too small of steps. Conversely, for $F=1$, convergence is slowest, meaning that our algorithm is taking too large of steps for this mutation factor. $F=0.5$ seems to be the just right value for this function in $\\mathbb{R}^5$. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Effect of `recombination`\n",
    "\n",
    "The final hyperparameter to be tuned is the crossover rate, or $C_r$ (called `recombination` in `DifferentialEvolutionSolver`). To create a trial solution at index $i$ with DE, indices are randomly chosen from the mutant vector, $\\mathbf{v}_i$ and the vector at index $i$ in the current population (also called the parent population). More explicitly, the trial vector $\\mathbf{u}_i$ follows the following relation\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{u}_i = (u_{i,j}) = \\begin{cases}\n",
    "v_{i,j} & \\text{if} ~ r \\leq C_r ~ \\text{or} ~ j = j_{\\text{rand}} \\\\\n",
    "x_{i,j} & \\text{otherwise}\n",
    "\\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $j_{rand}$ is a random choice from the range $[1, d]$ for a $d$-dimensional problem and $0 < r < 1$ is a uniform random number generated for each value of $j$. Clearly, $C_r$ is a probability, so it must be in $[0, 1]$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Small values of $C_r$ cause too few number of parameters to be changed, causing the resulting vector to likely be a single step along one dimension. Larger values cause almost all of the mutant vector's entries to be chosen, meaning possible good values for a particular dimension are less likely to be kept. It is recommended that $C_r \\in [0.3, 0.9]$. By default, `DifferentialEvolutionSolver` sets $C_r = 0.7$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x504 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "crossovers = [0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 0.9, 1]\n",
    "bests, variances = list(zip(*[solve(recombination_=c) for c in crossovers]))\n",
    "plot(bests, variances, [\"$C_r={}$\".format(c) for c in crossovers]);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Ackley function is seperable, meaning that each of its dimensions can be optimized independently while still reaching an optimum. As a result, the crossover rate matters less for this problem. It still has a mild influence on convergence at extreme values, but anything in the acceptable range of $[0.4, 0.9]$ works fine in this case."
   ]
  }
 ],
